  <title>Examples B</title>
  
<paragraphs>
  <title>Mag. Sources</title>
  
<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Two protons move together in the +x direction separated vertically by a distance r = 1 mm. 
      If their speed is <m>v = 1.00\times 10^{7} \,m/s,</m> find 
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          the electrical force between them (is it attractive or repulsive), 
        </li>
        <li>
          the magnetic force between them (is it attractive or repulsive), 
        </li>
        <li>
          the total electromagnetic force between them (is it attractive or repulsive), and 
        </li>
        <li>
          the ratio of electrical force to magnetic force. What do these answers become if v = 100 m/s?
        </li>
      </ol>
        </p>
        <image source="fig50.png" width="35%"> </image>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Given:	<m>r  =  1.00\times10^{-3} m;</m> <m>q = e = +1.6\times10^{-19} \,C; </m> 
      <m>m = 1.673\times10^{-27} \,kg; </m> <m>\epsilon_{o} = 8.85\times10^{-12} \,C^{2}/N.m^{2} ;</m>
      <m>\mu_{o} = 1.257\times10^{-6} \,W_{b}/A.m.</m>
    </p>
    <p>
     For <m> v=1.00\times10^{7} \,m/s</m>
     <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <me>
          E=kq/r^{2}=1.439\times10^{-3} \,N/C;
      </me>
      <me>
        F_{E}=qE=2.302\times10^{-22} \,N, \quad repulsive
      </me>
        </li>
      <li>
        <me>
          B=\frac{\mu_{o}}{4\pi}\frac{qv}{r^{2}} =1.6\times10^{-13} \,N/Am;
        </me>
        <me>
          F_{B}=qv B = 2.56\times10^{-25}\,N, \quad attractive
        </me>
        </li>
      <li>
       <me>
        F=F_{E}-F_{B}=2.299\times10^{-22}\,N, \quad repulsive;
       </me>
        </li>
      <li>
        <me>
          R=\frac{F_{E}}{F_{B}}=899;
        </me>
          </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
      For <m>v=1.00\times10^{2} \,m/s</m>
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
         <me>
          F_{E}=2.302\times10^{-22}\,N,\quad repulsive 
         </me>
         
        </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            B=  1.6\times10^{-18}\, N/Am, 
          </me>
          <me>
            F_{B}=2.56\times10^{-34}\,N, \quad attractive
          </me>
             </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            F=2.302\times10^{-22}\,N,\quad repulsive
          </me>
          </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            R = 8.99\times10^{11}.
          </me>
            </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A rectangular wire loop of width W = 10 cm and length L = 20 cm has a counter-clockwise 
        current I = 2 A. What is the magnitude and direction of the magnetic field at the central point. 
      </p>
      <image source="fig52.png" width="35%"> </image>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Given: <m>W=0.1\,m, \quad L= 0.2\,m, \quad I = 2\,A </m> 
      </p>
      <p>
        <me>
          B= B_{ab}+B_{bc}+B_{cd}+B_{da} = 2B_{ab} + 2B_{bc}
        </me>
        <me>
          B_{ab} = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{2a}{x\sqrt{(x^{2}+a^{2})}}; \quad a=W/2, \quad x=L/2 
        </me>
        <me>
          B_{bc} = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{2a}{x\sqrt{(x^{2}+a^{2})}}; \quad a=L/2,\quad x=W/2
        </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            <me>
              B= \frac{\mu_{o}I}{\pi W}\sqrt{5} = 1.79\times10^{-5}\,T
            </me>
            From the right hand rule, <m>\vec{B}</m> is out of the paper.
          </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
</paragraphs>

<paragraphs>
  <title>Ampere's Law</title>
  
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A long straight vertical wire carries an upward current of <m>I_{1} = 10 \,A.</m> 
        A rectangular coil of wire is located near the vertical wire as shown in the figure below. 
        If a = 10 cm, b = 30 cm, c = 50 cm, and <m>I_2 = 5 \,A</m>, what is the net force on the rectangular 
        coil due to the magnetic field of the straight line? 
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Given:	<m> I_{1} = 10 \,A; \quad a= 0.1 \,m; b=0.3\,m;</m> <m>c=0.5\,m; I_{2} = 5 \,A.</m>
      </p>
      <image source="fig54.png" width="35%"> </image>
      <p>
        <me>
          \frac{\vec{F_{a}}}{c}	 = \frac{\mu_{o}I_{1}I_{2} }{2\pi a}\hat{i}
        </me>
        <me>
          \frac{\vec{F_{b}}}{c}	 = \frac{\mu_{o}I_{1}I_{2} }{2\pi b}[-\hat{i}]
        </me>
        <me>
          \vec{F_{top}}=-\vec{F_{bottom}} 
        </me>
        <me>
          \vec{F}=\vec{F_{a}}+ \vec{F_{b}}+\vec{F_{top}} + \vec{F_{bottom}}
        </me>
        <me>
          \vec{F} = \frac{\mu_{o}I_{1}I_{2}c }{2\pi}\left(\frac{1}{a}-\frac{1}{b}\right)\hat{i}
        </me>
        <me>
          \vec{F}  = 3.33\times10^{-5} N \hat{i}
        </me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Derive the magnetic field at a distance r from a long straight wire carrying current I using Ampere's Law.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="fig55.png" width="35%"> </image>
      <p>
        Pick a circle centered on the wire and perpendicular to the wire. Due to the right 
        hand rule, the magnetic field must be tangent to the circle at every point. 
        Therefore, the dot product  <me>
          \vec{B}\cdot\vec{dl}   = B dl.
        </me>
         Due to symmetry, B must have the same magnitude at every point, so B is constant and Ampere's Law becomes:
      </p>
      <p>
        <me>
          \oint \vec{B}\cdot\vec{dl}   = \mu_{o}I 
        </me>
        <me>
          B\oint\,dl = B(2\pi r) = \mu_{o}I 
        </me>
        <me>
          B=\frac{\mu_{o}I }{2\pi r}
        </me>
        </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the magnetic field 
        <ol>
          <li>
            inside and
          </li>
          <li>
            outside a tightly wound toroid of N turns. 
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="fig56a.png" width="35%"> </image>
      <p>
        The figure above shows a cross section of the toroid showing the wires carrying the 
        current coming out of the paper on the outside of the toroid and into the paper 
        inside the toroid. Taking the path of the line integral in Ampere's law clockwise 
        around a circle centered on the toroid produces a symmetry that makes the magnetic 
        field <m>\vec{B}</m> constant in magnitude and everywhere parallel to the path so:
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
           <me> 
            \oint \vec{B}\cdot\vec{dl}   = \mu_{o}I
          </me>
           <me>
            B\oint dl  = B(2\pi r) =\mu_{o}NI
           </me>
           <me>
            B = \frac{\mu_{o}NI}{2\pi r} \quad \text{inside toroid}
           </me>
            </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              \oint \vec{B}\cdot\vec{dl} = \mu_{o}I 
            </me>
            <me>
              or, B = 0 \quad \text{outside toroid} 
            </me>
             </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Two long straight wires, suspended from a common point by a length L of string, 
        are directed into and out of the paper carrying equal but opposite currents as 
        shown in the figure below. If the length of the string is L = 1 m, the mass per 
        unit length of the wire is <m>\mu = 1 \,g/m,</m> and the angle each makes with 
        the vertical is <m>\theta = 10^{o},</m> find I, the current in each wire. 
      </p>
      <image source="fig57.png" width="35%"> </image>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Given: Length of the strings  L=1 m, mass per unit length  
        <m>\mu=\frac{mass}{length}=1\,g/m=0.001\,kg/m,</m> <m>\theta=10^{o},</m> and  
        <m>I_{1}=I_{2}=I=?</m>
      </p>
      <image source="fig57b.png" width="35%"> </image>
      <p>
        Force experienced by a current wire in an external magnetic field is given by  
        <me>
          F=IlB 
        </me>
        here, l is length of the wire.
        <me>
          B=\frac{\mu_{o}I}{2\pi r}
        </me>
        r is the seperation between the wires.
        <me>
          \therefore\quad F_{1}= \frac{I_{1}l_{1}\mu_{o}I_{2}}{2\pi r}
        </me>
        <men xml:id="eqn-ampr1">
          \frac{F_{1}}{l_{1}} = \frac{\mu_{o}I_{1}I_{2}}{2\pi r}  
        </men>
      From figure
      <me>
        T\cos\theta=mg = \mu l \,g
      </me>
      <men xml:id="eqn-ampr2">
        \text{or,}\quad T=\frac{\mu l g}{\cos\theta} 
      </men>
      <me>
        \text{also,}\quad \sin\theta=\frac{r/2}{L} = \frac{r}{2L}
      </me>
     <men xml:id="eqn-ampr3">
      \text{or,}\quad r=2L\sin\theta  
     </men>
     <me>
      \text{also,}\quad F_{1}=F_{2} = T\sin\theta
     </me>
     Therefore from eqn. <xref ref="eqn-ampr1"/>, we have - 
     <me>
      \frac{F_{1}}{l_{1}} =\frac{T\sin\theta}{l_{1}} =\frac{\mu_{o}I_{1}I_{2}}{2\pi r }
     </me>
     <me>
      \text{or,}\quad \frac{\mu l g \sin\theta}{l\cos\theta}=\frac{\mu_{o}I^{2}}{2\pi 2\sin\theta }
     </me>
     <m>[\because I_{1}=I_{2}=I]</m>
      <me>
        \text{or,}\quad I^{2}= \frac{\mu \,g \tan\theta \sin\theta 4\pi}{\mu_{o}} 
      </me>
      <me>
        = \frac{4\pi\times 0.001\times9.8\times\tan10^{o}\sin10^{o}}{4\pi\times10^{-7}} = 54.77 \,A
      </me>
        </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
</paragraphs>



